docs.abstract: Mr. Zuckerberg’s planned visit to Brussels, following the C.E.O.’s testimony before Congress last month, highlights global concern over data privacy.
docs.snippet: Mr. Zuckerberg’s planned visit to Brussels, following the C.E.O.’s testimony before Congress last month, highlights global concern over data privacy.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Mark Zuckerberg, Facebook’s chief executive, plans to meet with members of the European Parliament as early as next week, the latest stop in a wide-ranging apology tour over the social network’s use of people’s personal data.

headline.main: Mark Zuckerberg to Meet European Parliament Members Over Facebook’s Data Use
headline.print_headline: Zuckerberg to Meet With E.U. Leaders Amid Outcry Over Data Use

byline.original: By Prashant S. Rao, Sheera Frenkel and Milan Schreuer

docs.abstract: The 120-year-old magazine invited a history professor to critique its past coverage of race, and showed little defensiveness in accepting his findings.
docs.snippet: The 120-year-old magazine invited a history professor to critique its past coverage of race, and showed little defensiveness in accepting his findings.
docs.lead_paragraph: As National Geographic editors prepared an issue dedicated to race, they realized the 130-year-old magazine might face questions about its troubled history on the subject.

headline.main: National Geographic Acknowledges Its Racist Past Coverage
headline.print_headline: National Geographic Accepts Findings That Its Past Coverage Was Racist

docs.abstract: A stringent set of data protection rules will take effect in Europe in May. Facebook, Google and others are working overtime to be ready.
docs.snippet: A stringent set of data protection rules will take effect in Europe in May. Facebook, Google and others are working overtime to be ready.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Over the past two months, Google has started letting people around the world choose what data they want to share with its various products, including Gmail and Google Docs.

headline.main: Tech Giants Brace for Europe’s New Data Privacy Rules
headline.print_headline: Tech Giants Await Change On Privacy In Europe

docs.abstract: The $16 billion deal will put America’s largest operator of physical retail stores in direct competition with Amazon in a promising but risky market.
docs.snippet: The $16 billion deal will put America’s largest operator of physical retail stores in direct competition with Amazon in a promising but risky market.
docs.lead_paragraph: MUMBAI — Walmart said on Wednesday it reached a $16 billion deal to buy a majority stake in Flipkart, India’s leading e-commerce platform, in a sizable bet on a vibrant but risky new market.

headline.main: Walmart Takes Control of India’s Flipkart in E-Commerce Gamble

docs.abstract: Classical music has long had a place in commercials, but now it is being used as more than a jokey device or a signal of sophistication.
docs.snippet: Classical music has long had a place in commercials, but now it is being used as more than a jokey device or a signal of sophistication.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the figures on a graffiti mural came to vibrant life in a Coke commercial that debuted during the Olympics last month, they leapt, rolled and scaled buildings to the accompaniment of “In the Hall of the Mountain King,” a movement of Edvard Grieg’s “Peer Gynt” Suite.

headline.main: Selling Products With a Swelling Score
headline.print_headline: Classical Music Keeps Ad Makers Coming Back

docs.abstract: The final Boeing 747 flight by any commercial United States airline took to the sky recently, with some tears and farewells. But a new life for the plane beckons.
docs.snippet: The final Boeing 747 flight by any commercial United States airline took to the sky recently, with some tears and farewells. But a new life for the plane beckons.
docs.lead_paragraph: MARANA, Ariz. —  There may be no airliner as recognizable as the Boeing 747,  the world’s first jumbo jet, with its iconic hump of an upper deck. For aviation fans, the introduction of the “Queen of the Skies” was a triumph of engineering and grace: unprecedented size and speed with spiral-staircase international glamour.

headline.main: The 747 Had a Great Run. But Farewell Doesn’t Mean the End.
headline.print_headline: In Arizona, New Life Beckons  A Deserving Retiree: The 747

byline.original: By Zach Wichter and Dustin Chambers

docs.abstract: Companies like Bacardi are increasingly going beyond traditional advertising to interact directly with the public.
docs.snippet: Companies like Bacardi are increasingly going beyond traditional advertising to interact directly with the public.
docs.lead_paragraph: During Prohibition, tourists arriving at the Havana airport were often greeted by Rafael Valiente, a popular bartender in Cuba and the first brand ambassador for Bacardi rum. Mr. Valiente, known as Pappy, would frequently take them to Bacardi’s private bar in its Havana office building and treat them to a rum cocktail.

headline.main: Have a Drink on Us. And Tell Your Friends.
headline.print_headline: Have a Drink on Us. And Tell Your Friends.

docs.abstract: With unemployment below 4 percent for the first time since 2000, the recovery’s duration is remarkable, but lagging pay remains a riddle.
docs.snippet: With unemployment below 4 percent for the first time since 2000, the recovery’s duration is remarkable, but lagging pay remains a riddle.
docs.lead_paragraph: The last time the unemployment rate fell below the 4 percent threshold was in 2000, during a period of frenetic activity remembered as the dot-com boom.

headline.main: Jobless Rate Looks Like Old Times, but the Economy Doesn’t
headline.print_headline: Jobless Rate Dips To Lowest Level Since 2000 Boom

docs.abstract: Dropping ratings, especially among young people, and more viewing options mean broadcast TV is in a precarious position as it pitches itself to advertisers.
docs.snippet: Dropping ratings, especially among young people, and more viewing options mean broadcast TV is in a precarious position as it pitches itself to advertisers.
docs.lead_paragraph: Television networks will draw hordes of advertisers to New York City this week for their annual bonanza of presentations and parties, a decades-old tradition known as the upfronts that is meant to dazzle marketers and loosen their purse strings.

headline.main: Why Traditional TV Is in Trouble
headline.print_headline: No Choice for Marketers  But to Rethink TV Ads

byline.original: By Sapna Maheshwari and John Koblin

docs.abstract: The $2 billion wiped off the company’s shares is a reminder to directors on all company boards that misbehavior has become a financial risk.
docs.snippet: The $2 billion wiped off the company’s shares is a reminder to directors on all company boards that misbehavior has become a financial risk.
docs.lead_paragraph: There are some risks that investors can’t price. An allegation of sexual misconduct against a chief executive has now been added to that list. Wynn Resorts shares plunged more than 10 percent on Friday afternoon, wiping $2 billion off the company’s value, after The Wall Street Journal reported that such accusations had been leveled at the company’s founder, chief executive, chairman and biggest shareholder, Steve Wynn. Mr. Wynn promptly dismissed the allegations to Reuters as “preposterous.” The loss of value is a reminder to directors on all company boards that even an unproven suggestion of sexual harassment is now a financial risk.

headline.main: Wynn Resorts’ Slide Shows Sexual Misconduct Is a Financial Risk
